
[1]phlem

   PHLEM, n. [Gr. inflammation; and pituitous matter, to burn; hence the
   word must have originally expressed the matter formed by suppuration.]

   1. Cold animal fluid; water matter; one of the four humors of which the
   ancients supposed the blood to be composed.

   2. In common usage, bronchial mucus; the thick viscid matter secreted
   in the throat.

   3. Among chimists, water, or the water of distillation.

   4. Dullness; coldness; sluggishness; indifference.
